- `f u_outer` is defined as `rotproj_outer_unit S w`, where `S = P` and `w = pc.w`.
- `rotproj_outer_unit P pc.w` is defined as `inner (rotM (P 0) (P 1) S) w / ‖S‖`.
- We're looking at the partial derivative with respect to `P 0` (the first coordinate of the point `P`).

The partial derivative of `f u_outer` with respect to `P 0` is:
`∂(f u_outer)/∂P 0 = ∂(inner (rotM (P 0) (P 1) P) w / ‖P‖)/∂P 0`.

Using the quotient rule for differentiation:
`∂(A/B)/∂x = (∂A/∂x * B - A * ∂B/∂x) / B²`.

Let `A = inner (rotM (P 0) (P 1) P) w` and `B = ‖P‖`.
`∂A/∂P 0` is the derivative of the inner product with respect to `P 0`.
`∂B/∂P 0` is the derivative of the norm with respect to `P 0`.

`∂A/∂P 0 = inner (d/dP 0 (rotM (P 0) (P 1) P)) w + inner (rotM (P 0) (P 1) P) (d/dP 0 w)`.
Since `w` is constant with respect to `P`, the second term is 0.
`d/dP 0 (rotM (P 0) (P 1) P)` is the derivative of the rotation matrix applied to `P`.
`d/dP 0 (rotM (P 0) (P 1) P) = d/dP 0 (Matrix.vecHead (P) • Matrix.vecHead (P) • Matrix.vecHead (P) + ...)` (explicitly calculating the derivative of each entry of the rotation matrix applied to P).

`d/dP 0 (‖P‖) = P 0 / ‖P‖`.

So:
`∂(A/B)/∂P 0 = ( (inner (d/dP 0 (rotM (P 0) (P 1) P)) w) * ‖P‖ - inner (rotM (P 0) (P 1) P) w * (P 0 / ‖P‖) ) / ‖P‖²`.

This simplifies to:
`inner (d/dP 0 (rotM (P 0) (P 1) P)) w / ‖P‖ - inner (rotM (P 0) (P 1) P) w * P 0 / ‖P‖³`.
`inner (d/dP 0 (rotM (P 0) (P 1) P)) w / ‖P‖ - inner (rotM (P 0) (P 1) P) w * P 0 / ‖P‖³`.
`inner (d/dP 0 (rotM (P 0) (P 1) P)) w / ‖P‖ - inner (rotM (P 0) (P 1) P) w * P 0 / ‖P‖³`.

The term `inner (d/dP 0 (rotM (P 0) (P 1) P)) w` is `inner (d/dP 0 (R(θ₂) R(θ₁) R(α) P)) w`. This is `inner (R(θ₂) R(θ₁) R(α) d/dP 0 P) w`. Since `d/dP 0 P` is the vector `(1, 0, 0)`, this is `inner (R(θ₂) R(θ₁) R(α) (1, 0, 0)) w`. This is `inner (x-axis direction vector after rotations) w`. This is `⟨pbar.rotM₂θ P, pc.w⟩` if we consider the derivative of the x-axis direction vector with respect to P 0.

